The Russian Ambassador to Nigeria, Alexey Shebarshin, has declared that his home government is waiting for the federal government to put its house in order for them to sign the Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) for the completion of the Ajaokuta Steel complex. He spoke yesterday when Kogi State governor, Yahaya Bello, paid him a courtesy visit at the Russian Embassy in Abuja for discussions ahead of the planned completion and revival of the steel plant. Shebarshin told Governor Bello that the Russian government was fully ready to come down Nigeria to complete the complex following President Muhammadu Buhari’s visit to his Russian counterpart, Vladimir Putin in October 2019. Earlier, Governor Bello had said that his visit was to convey the goodwill message of the people of Kogi State to the Russian government through the embassy for the October 22, 2019 Sochi Agreement between the Russia and Nigeria on the revival of Ajaokuta Steel Company Limited. The governor assured the ambassador of the readiness of his administration to see that Ajaokuta works for Kogi people and Nigeria at large. He also told the envoy that the state possesses enormous opportunities and called on the Russian government to partner with his administration to develop the agricultural and energy sectors in the state. The governor, who praised President Buhari for taking up negotiations with the Russia t to revive the steel company, pointed out that Ajaokuta would make Nigeria the industrial hub of the world. The governor was accompanied on the visit by his chief of staff, Jamiu Abdulkareem Asuku, the commissioner for finance and economic planning, Idris Asiwaju Asiru, the state accountant-general, Jibrin Momoh, and the auditor-general, Okala Yusuf.